name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: Dear creatives, you are worth more than they are telling you.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: Don’t buy into the hype.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: I’ve done free work in my past so that the next generation doesn’t have to. Don’t repeat the cycle. We’ve made our culture popular enough to demand proper pay.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: Value does not equal money. It means equal exchange. So if you’re giving, make sure you’re receiving in some way. Fair wages, marketing, sales, something. Equal exchange of energy.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: Don’t make decisions through fear, you’re worth way more than “fear wages”.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: The decisions you make are bigger than you. What you charge, you contribute to the value of your culture. Bringing down your value brings down the value of the craft you’re marketing. It’s bad enough we have to fight outside of our community.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: There’s been plenty of times in my life where I had zero in my account, got offered a job for less than my worth... Starving, hungry, and still willing to say no. Bills due, but still said no. You have to be willing to starve so your brand doesn’t.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: Separate yourself from your brand. Then separate your brand from your culture. You’ve got to be willing to be hungry and say “no” to an unfair exchange of value.

name: Blacka Di Danca
tweet: People’s true colors show in times of crisis.

name: Allan Smith
tweet: Carmelo Martinez was maybe 3 inches from hitting the second-most legendary home run in team history. Instead, he’s a forgotten part of the early 90s Pirates

name: Allan Smith
tweet: All of this is to say, with the lack of live sports now and people digging through the past, would love to read an enterprising piece on Martinez and this game all these years later - if he’s even willing to talk about it @TheAthleticPGH @DKPghSports @PGSportsNow

name: Allan Smith
tweet: Cincinnati’s right fielder, Glenn Braggs, is moving with his back to the wall. He perfectly times a leap and robs Martinez of the go-ahead 9th inning home run.   Pirates would’ve been up 3-2 in the 9th. Instead the next batter strikes out and the Reds go to the World Series

name: Allan Smith
tweet: But Martinez will have one chance for redemption after that awful bunt. Comes in the 9th inning. Bonds on first. One out. Pirates down 2-1.  Martinez works the count and then unleashes a rip to deep right center field. Exactly where he hit his double, only this one is better hit

name: Allan Smith
tweet: Martinez inexplicably lays down a bunt - well, inexplicable by today’s standards.   Martinez had maybe put down 2 bunts his whole career. He pops up the pitch. First out. Next 2 guys hit fly balls for outs that, had the bunt worked, both would’ve scored the runners on sac flies

name: Allan Smith
tweet: The Pirates only recorded one hit in the game, an RBI double from Martinez that tied the game in the 5th inning.  Fast forward to the top of the 7th. Game still tied 1-1. Martinez steps up to bat with Bonilla at 2nd and Bonds at 1st. No outs.

name: Allan Smith
tweet: Martinez had a very brief career with the Pirates, only appearing in 25 combined regular and postseason games. But he did enjoy a 9-year big league career with more than 1,000 plate appearances and 100 home runs.  But now, to his Game 6 performance

name: Allan Smith
tweet: Martinez had, in my estimation, one of the most absurd games in a high-stakes do-or-die scenario. And it’s never discussed  Basically nothing written on his performance in the decades that followed. Have never heard him discussed

name: Allan Smith
tweet: Had my first moment watching an old game and going “wtf I had no idea that happened!”  Game 6 of the 1990 NLCS. Pirates vs. Reds. Reds won 2-1 & advanced to the World Series.  My surprise centered on a little known guy who played 1B for the Pirates that day, Carmelo Martinez
